229
00:12:16,367 --> 00:12:19,067
Isn't this a knife? It's dangerous!

230
00:12:19,067 --> 00:12:20,767
But, I wonder if it's for real.

231
00:12:20,767 --> 00:12:22,567
It's real!

232
00:12:22,567 --> 00:12:26,267
The president is a famous knife collector.

233
00:12:26,267 --> 00:12:28,767
There's a lot of talk about his collection with our clients,

234
00:12:28,767 --> 00:12:31,167
so he has a lot decorated at the company too.

235
00:12:33,967 --> 00:12:35,467
Sorry to keep you guys waiting!

236
00:12:36,667 --> 00:12:37,967
I've made up my mind!

237
00:12:37,967 --> 00:12:43,167
We're going to put AIMS of the 3rd development section on the market!

238
00:12:43,167 --> 00:12:45,567
And, we're going to consolidate the first

239
00:12:45,567 --> 00:12:48,067
and second development sections into one section.

240
00:12:50,167 --> 00:12:52,367
Will everyone except Hiramatsu leave the room?

241
00:12:52,367 --> 00:12:54,967
-President! -I'll talk to you later!

242
00:12:54,967 --> 00:12:57,567
Thank you so much also, Mr. Mouri.

243
00:12:57,567 --> 00:13:00,567
Please relax in the reception corner.

244
00:13:00,567 --> 00:13:05,367
After we finish work, I'd like to talk with you over drinks.

245
00:13:06,767 --> 00:13:08,567
Wow, that'd be just great!

246
00:13:09,967 --> 00:13:12,767
Okay, I'll be waiting then.

247
00:13:13,767 --> 00:13:17,967
They can't dispatch a repair car until the fog clears up after all.

248
00:13:17,967 --> 00:13:20,267
I'll bet you're really relieved

249
00:13:20,267 --> 00:13:22,967
because you can drink all you like now!

250
00:13:22,967 --> 00:13:25,367
Well, I guess I'll go make some coffee then.

251
00:13:25,367 --> 00:13:28,367
Oh, let me help you!

252
00:13:28,367 --> 00:13:30,467
I have to go to the restroom.

253
00:13:30,467 --> 00:13:33,767
The restroom's beyond the room we were in just a while ago.

254
00:13:33,767 --> 00:13:36,067
It's the second door to your left.

255
00:13:36,067 --> 00:13:37,167
Okay!

256
00:13:37,667 --> 00:13:40,067
Please nullify my contract with you!

257
00:13:40,067 --> 00:13:42,967
I'm fed up having to work under you!

258
00:13:44,067 --> 00:13:47,167
Do I look like a softy who would say, "Yes, of course",

259
00:13:47,167 --> 00:13:50,367
and nullify our contract?

260
00:13:50,367 --> 00:13:51,767
No...

261
00:13:51,767 --> 00:13:54,967
so I have already made appropriate arrangements.

262
00:13:56,067 --> 00:13:59,267
So, that you would by no means refuse to do so.

263
00:13:59,267 --> 00:14:01,567
I'm definite that you won't refuse.

264
00:14:07,689 --> 00:14:09,589
They're sure taking their time.

265
00:14:09,589 --> 00:14:11,689
He's probably being threatened

266
00:14:11,689 --> 00:14:14,589
and signing a ruthless contract or something.

267
00:14:14,589 --> 00:14:16,589
Serves him right.

268
00:14:16,589 --> 00:14:18,589
A ruthless contract?

269
00:14:18,589 --> 00:14:19,689
Yes.

270
00:14:19,689 --> 00:14:22,289
What does it mean to nullify a contract?

271
00:14:22,289 --> 00:14:23,389
Gosh!

272
00:14:23,389 --> 00:14:25,689
Keep out of this, kid!

273
00:14:25,689 --> 00:14:29,989
Sonny, did you hear Hiramatsu say so to the president?

274
00:14:29,989 --> 00:14:34,889
Don't tell me Hiramatsu's planning to quit the company?

275
00:14:34,889 --> 00:14:38,489
Which means that you're all contract employees?

276
00:14:38,489 --> 00:14:42,789
Yes, when the president finds a talented developer,

277
00:14:42,789 --> 00:14:45,289
he forces the developer to sign a long-term contract with him,

278
00:14:45,289 --> 00:14:47,889
and makes it difficult for the person to quit easily.

279
00:14:47,889 --> 00:14:50,989
By force? No.

280
00:14:50,989 --> 00:14:52,289
It's true.

281
00:14:52,289 --> 00:14:54,689
The president's physique is as you saw him.

282
00:14:54,689 --> 00:14:57,689
Besides, he carries a "dan" in karate.

283
00:14:57,689 --> 00:15:00,789
Even if he doesn't really hit you and stops just before hitting,

284
00:15:00,789 --> 00:15:02,289
a weak hearted person would panic

285
00:15:02,289 --> 00:15:04,289
and sign the contract immediately.

286
00:15:04,289 --> 00:15:05,889
Oh, no.

287
00:15:05,889 --> 00:15:09,089
Well, Kasahara and I have been here

288
00:15:09,089 --> 00:15:10,089
since the previous president was our boss,

289
00:15:10,089 --> 00:15:12,289
so we've been spared that karate scare

290
00:15:12,289 --> 00:15:14,889
but all the young staff are being tempered here

291
00:15:14,889 --> 00:15:17,489
at this study dormitory.

292
00:15:17,489 --> 00:15:20,089
Moreover, he takes advantage of tax exemptions

293
00:15:20,089 --> 00:15:23,789
and uses company funds to cover everything

294
00:15:23,789 --> 00:15:28,089
from his hobby of collecting knives to giving gifts to women.

295
00:15:28,089 --> 00:15:32,489
Even on our way here... take a look at this!

296
00:15:34,989 --> 00:15:36,089
What's that?

297
00:15:36,089 --> 00:15:38,289
Strange, that's the sound of a car...

298
00:15:42,489 --> 00:15:44,289
It's Mr. Hiramatsu's car.

299
00:15:44,289 --> 00:15:45,689
I wonder what's going on.

300
00:15:46,989 --> 00:15:49,789
The window on the other side!

301
00:15:49,789 --> 00:15:51,089
It's open.

302
00:15:51,089 --> 00:15:52,489
No way?

303
00:15:53,589 --> 00:15:54,989
Conan?

304
00:16:03,789 --> 00:16:06,089
-This is? -President.

305
00:16:06,789 --> 00:16:09,189
President? President!

306
00:16:09,189 --> 00:16:10,989
Please get a hold of yourself!

307
00:16:10,989 --> 00:16:12,889
Please stay back!

308
00:16:13,789 --> 00:16:16,089
Mr. Umetani, are you okay?

309
00:16:19,889 --> 00:16:21,089
He's still breathing!

310
00:16:21,089 --> 00:16:22,189
President!

311
00:16:22,189 --> 00:16:24,389
Ran! Get the ambulance and the police!

312
00:16:24,389 --> 00:16:26,489
Yes!

313
00:16:26,489 --> 00:16:30,189
Let's leave the rest to Ran and go after Mr. Hiramatsu!

314
00:16:32,389 --> 00:16:33,589
The car in the foreground!

315
00:16:33,589 --> 00:16:35,289
I've got the keys.

316
00:16:35,289 --> 00:16:38,589
It's the president's but I drive it so...

317
00:16:38,589 --> 00:16:41,089
Wait! There's a flat!

318
00:16:41,089 --> 00:16:43,389
This side is super flat too!

319
00:16:43,389 --> 00:16:46,189
The tires of my car are flat too!

320
00:16:46,189 --> 00:16:47,589
Darn!

321
00:16:57,989 --> 00:16:59,589
In the mountains like this,

322
00:16:59,589 --> 00:17:02,389
it's faster to take him to the hospital by car

323
00:17:02,389 --> 00:17:06,389
than to wait for an ambulance but...

324
00:17:06,389 --> 00:17:07,989
-Oh, president. -President!

325
00:17:07,989 --> 00:17:09,189
Mr. Umetani.

326
00:17:09,189 --> 00:17:11,589
President, please get a hold of yourself!

327
00:17:15,589 --> 00:17:17,489
The knife fell off!

328
00:17:17,489 --> 00:17:19,489
What's going on?

329
00:17:23,889 --> 00:17:25,489
This is?

330
00:17:25,489 --> 00:17:28,789
The knife poked into the cigar case!

331
00:17:28,789 --> 00:17:32,989
Which means that the cigar case saved his life?

332
00:17:36,489 --> 00:17:38,889
-President! -Thank god!

333
00:17:40,289 --> 00:17:43,789
Mr. Umetani, what in the world happened?

334
00:17:45,689 --> 00:17:49,589
Hiramatsu suddenly stabbed me with a knife.

335
00:18:23,689 --> 00:18:27,389
It seems that there was a thick fog at the time of the accident

336
00:18:27,389 --> 00:18:30,189
and besides this slope is steep and the curve is very sharp...

337
00:18:30,189 --> 00:18:32,789
It's most likely that he couldn't steer fast enough

338
00:18:32,789 --> 00:18:35,089
while he was on the run.

339
00:18:35,089 --> 00:18:37,889
Yeah, most likely...

340
00:18:37,889 --> 00:18:41,089
All the tires of the other cars were flat,

341
00:18:41,089 --> 00:18:46,689
so there was no reason for him to rush as much as he did, though.

342
00:18:46,689 --> 00:18:49,689
If he could think on that line,

343
00:18:49,689 --> 00:18:52,789
he wouldn't have gotten enraged and stab somebody.

344
00:18:52,789 --> 00:18:54,689
Exactly!

345
00:18:54,689 --> 00:18:57,689
Just as expected of you Mr. Mouri, very sharp deduction!

346
00:18:57,689 --> 00:18:59,889
Well...

347
00:19:05,989 --> 00:19:08,589
Well, the victim is only slightly hurt,

348
00:19:08,589 --> 00:19:11,389
so we'll be able to get at the motive of the stabber right away.

349
00:19:11,389 --> 00:19:12,489
Right.

350
00:19:17,489 --> 00:19:19,489
Sonny! What are you doing?

351
00:19:19,489 --> 00:19:21,789
You shouldn't be in here.

352
00:19:21,789 --> 00:19:24,589
What's this mirror?

353
00:19:24,589 --> 00:19:26,389
Oh, that?

354
00:19:26,389 --> 00:19:27,989
It's called a corner mirror.

355
00:19:27,989 --> 00:19:30,189
From here on down, it's the land of that company

356
00:19:30,189 --> 00:19:31,589
and it's a private road.

357
00:19:31,589 --> 00:19:33,989
It seems that nobody is here now, though.

358
00:19:33,989 --> 00:19:36,289
See, there's the sign of the company.

359
00:19:36,289 --> 00:19:37,889
It says public welfare facility.

360
00:19:37,889 --> 00:19:40,889
Well, it's like a company villa.

361
00:19:40,889 --> 00:19:42,889
This large rock is really a pain

362
00:19:42,889 --> 00:19:44,689
and it blocks vision when going in and out

363
00:19:44,689 --> 00:19:46,189
making it really dangerous.

364
00:19:46,189 --> 00:19:48,789
On this side, there's this sharp curve too.

365
00:19:48,789 --> 00:19:52,189
There's a curve mirror there for the public road too.

366
00:19:52,189 --> 00:19:54,989
Because I'm in charge around here,

367
00:19:54,989 --> 00:19:59,389
I wanted a corner mirror for the private road!

368
00:19:59,389 --> 00:20:01,389
I see.

369
00:20:01,389 --> 00:20:05,389
The position of the mirror is not right.

370
00:20:05,389 --> 00:20:07,789
It's good that they made a large one,

371
00:20:07,789 --> 00:20:09,889
but I wonder if the wind blows it out of place.

372
00:20:09,889 --> 00:20:11,889
It was okay in the day time!

373
00:20:11,889 --> 00:20:14,589
Oh, I think it's better not to fix it.

374
00:20:14,589 --> 00:20:18,689
It could've been the reason the accident occurred, right?

375
00:20:18,689 --> 00:20:21,289
Oh, no!

376
00:20:21,289 --> 00:20:27,089
And, Mr. Mouri wants you to check the brakes of the car right away!

377
00:20:27,089 --> 00:20:29,189
Mr. Mouri want me to?

378
00:20:29,189 --> 00:20:30,289
I see!

379
00:20:30,289 --> 00:20:32,789
The brakes may have not been working.

380
00:20:32,789 --> 00:20:35,889
I'll ask using the wireless so wait a while, okay?

381
00:20:35,889 --> 00:20:37,189
Conan!

382
00:20:37,189 --> 00:20:39,889
Just what are you doing in a place like this!

383
00:20:39,889 --> 00:20:43,089
Dad's angry because he wants you to come back up.

384
00:20:43,089 --> 00:20:44,789
I'm sorry.

385
00:20:44,789 --> 00:20:46,389
Hurry, quick.

386
00:20:46,389 --> 00:20:48,089
Oh, wait.

387
00:20:48,889 --> 00:20:50,589
I'm sorry to keep you waiting.

388
00:20:50,589 --> 00:20:53,089
I tell you! Stop scampering around!

389
00:20:53,089 --> 00:20:54,689
I'm going to leave you here!

390
00:20:54,689 --> 00:20:56,289
I'm sorry.

391
00:20:56,289 --> 00:20:58,489
Calm down, Mr. Mouri.

392
00:20:58,489 --> 00:20:59,889
Mr. Mouri!

393
00:21:01,289 --> 00:21:03,189
Inspector Yokomizo!

394
00:21:03,189 --> 00:21:06,089
About your question a while ago...

395
00:21:06,889 --> 00:21:11,389
It seems that the brake oil of the car was completely gone.

396
00:21:11,389 --> 00:21:13,789
-Huh? -What did you just say?

397
00:21:13,789 --> 00:21:16,489
I can't tell for sure whether it happened

398
00:21:16,489 --> 00:21:18,089
because of the shock of the accident

399
00:21:18,089 --> 00:21:19,689
or whether it happened before the accident,

400
00:21:19,689 --> 00:21:22,789
but the tube seems to have come off.

401
00:21:22,789 --> 00:21:25,189
Which means, Mr. Mouri...

402
00:21:25,189 --> 00:21:28,689
the oil leaked out and the brakes may not have been working.

403
00:21:30,389 --> 00:21:32,489
It's only natural for him to have gotten into an accident

404
00:21:32,489 --> 00:21:34,589
on this mountainous road.

405
00:21:36,189 --> 00:21:37,889
Strange.

406
00:21:37,889 --> 00:21:40,589
There are too many strange things involved.

407
00:21:40,589 --> 00:21:43,689
A person who gets enraged, stabs someone and flees,

408
00:21:43,689 --> 00:21:44,989
flattens the tires of everyone's car

409
00:21:44,989 --> 00:21:47,289
because he doesn't want anyone to come after him.

410
00:21:47,289 --> 00:21:51,689
This same person panics and steers his car out of control,

411
00:21:51,689 --> 00:21:53,889
and falls over the cliff to his death.

412
00:21:55,289 --> 00:21:57,989
The curve mirror that was facing the wrong way.

413
00:21:58,889 --> 00:22:01,689
Brake oil that was completely gone.

414
00:22:03,389 --> 00:22:05,489
Something smells fishy.

415
00:22:05,489 --> 00:22:07,389
Very fishy!

416
00:23:45,989 --> 00:23:49,689
A rope, a stun gun and a death note.

417
00:23:49,689 --> 00:23:52,289
A death note? What's going on?

418
00:23:53,889 --> 00:23:55,789
What's this?

419
00:23:55,789 --> 00:23:56,889
What's wrong?

420
00:23:56,889 --> 00:23:59,089
Ran, please call Inspector Yokomizo and the others

421
00:23:59,089 --> 00:24:01,789
and tell them to come back!

422
00:24:01,789 --> 00:24:07,489
This is a cleverly schemed case of homicide!

423
00:24:07,789 --> 00:24:09,289
Next Conan,

424
00:24:09,289 --> 00:24:13,489
"The Lucky Cigar Case (Part 2)"

425
00:24:14,257 --> 00:24:16,457
Next Conan's Hint:

426
00:24:16,457 --> 00:24:18,657
"Cigar"

427
00:24:18,657 --> 00:24:20,457
Dad, which of the massage chairs was good?

428
00:24:20,457 --> 00:24:22,157
I can't tell unless I get to drink some beer.

429
00:24:22,157 --> 00:24:23,503
Talk about hopeless.

